node.text:
It’s International Youth Day! 
••••
Thanks to the good folks @npsyouth for sharing. 
•
🌈 Dare to Dream! It’s #InternationalYouthDay!

Why do people come to 🌳 national parks? National parks are places for fun, discovery, exploration, wellness, and service. The National Park Service’s Youth and Young Adult Programs are designed to connect kids, teens, and young adults just like you (up to age 30 and military veterans 35 years old or under), with opportunities at national parks sites to contribute to our nation’s rich natural, cultural, historical, and recreational resources in your own way. Learn more about our programs ➡️ 
https://www.nps.gov/subjects/youthprograms/index.htm 

⭐️ Everyday someone like you becomes a wildland firefighter, a biologist, a teacher, a trail-builder, a museum curator, and a park ranger. And, like you, they were once earning scout badges, volunteering, and just having fun hiking and biking in the great outdoors.

From 🤸‍♂️ Junior Ranger, Scout Ranger, and Girl Scout Ranger Programs, to NPS-YMCA camps and Boys and Girls Club Ultimate Journey, Youth Conservation Corps, internships, fellowships, apprenticeships & volunteer opportunities, there is a place for you in the NPS family. Join us!

Moments that make memories for a lifetime are National Park moments. 
•••••
Thanks to our friend Evan @wexplorations for sharing from his adventure. 
•
The grand finale to our time in @greatsmokynps: a glorious sunset, complete with the rolling fog of the mountains and, miraculously enough, a glowing red sun. I was spellbound by this. This was exactly the mental image of The Smokies that sustained me during these long and hard months of isolation and worry. To see it realized on the last night of our time here felt strangely inevitable; this wonderful moment I’d been thinking of for over a year was real and I was getting to see it. This fantastic sunset will be with me forever and I am so thankful I got to see it.
